"# Appendix ‚Äî The Verbs Cookbook

Every math verb in the CORE set gets its own entry here. Three or four runnable examples per verb, verified against `bin/motoi eval`. The order roughly follows: constants first, then unary operations, then binary and n-ary, then the K-6 pedagogy verbs that return tagged data rather than a single number.

Read this appendix the way you would read a recipe card index. You are not meant to read it front-to-back. You are meant to jump to the verb you need, copy the example that matches your situation, and go.

---

## Constants

The three named constants come with two spellings each. `math/pi`, `math/tau`, `math/e` live in the math namespace. `const/pi`, `const/tau`, `const/e`, `const/phi` live in the const namespace and include the golden ratio. Every one of them is a nullary procedure ‚Äî you *call* it, you do not just name it.

```scheme
(math/pi)              ; => 3.141592653589793
(math/tau)             ; => 6.283185307179586
(math/e)               ; => 2.718281828459045
(const/tau)            ; => 6.283185307179586
(const/phi)            ; => 1.618033988749895
```

Two things to notice. First, `math/tau` is exactly `(* 2 (math/pi))` ‚Äî one full turn around a circle. When you sweep an angle from zero to `(math/tau)`, you go all the way around and come home. Second, `const/phi` ‚Äî the golden ratio ‚Äî is the positive root of `x^2 = x + 1`. It shows up in leaf spirals, sunflower seeds, and any place where a system grows by adding to itself.

```scheme
(* 2 (math/pi))                        ; => 6.283185307179586
(- (* (const/phi) (const/phi)) (const/phi))  ; => 1
```

The second line is the golden-ratio identity: `phi^2 - phi = 1`. Motoi's math prints the rounded result cleanly; a floating-point comparison at the digit level might show a residue of `1e-16` depending on the host.

---

## Rounding: `math/floor`, `math/ceil`, `math/round-half-up`

Three ways to turn a real number into an integer. `math/floor` always rounds toward negative infinity; `math/ceil` always rounds toward positive infinity; `math/round-half-up` splits ties away from zero (which is the rounding rule most schoolbooks teach, and the one JavaScript's built-in `Math.round` gets wrong for negatives).

```scheme
(math/floor 3.7)                ; => 3
(math/floor -3.2)               ; => -4
(math/ceil 3.2)                 ; => 4
(math/ceil -3.7)                ; => -3
(math/round-half-up 2.5)        ; => 3
(math/round-half-up -2.5)       ; => -3
(math/round-half-up 2.4)        ; => 2
```

Notice how `math/floor -3.2` gives `-4`, not `-3`. Floor is *always downward*, and downward on the negative side is *more negative*. This trips people up.

---

## Powers and roots: `math/square`, `math/cube`, `math/hypot`

`math/square` and `math/cube` are convenience verbs ‚Äî they exist because raising a number to the second or third power is common enough that the parenthesis-noise of `(* x x)` deserves a name.

```scheme
(math/square 7)                 ; => 49
(math/cube 4)                   ; => 64
(math/square (+ 3 4))           ; => 49
```

`math/hypot` computes the length of the hypotenuse of a right triangle given the two legs. It is a two-argument verb, and it uses the standard Pythagorean formula under the hood ‚Äî but implemented so it does not overflow when the legs are very large.

```scheme
(math/hypot 3 4)                ; => 5
(math/hypot 5 12)               ; => 13
(math/hypot 1 1)                ; => 1.4142135623730951
```

The last one is the diagonal of a unit square, which is `(math/sqrt 2)`.

---

## Interpolation: `math/lerp`

Linear interpolation. `(math/lerp a b t)` returns `a` when `t` is zero, `b` when `t` is one, and blends linearly in between. This is the single most useful animation primitive in the language.

```scheme
(math/lerp 0 100 0.25)          ; => 25
(math/lerp 0 100 0.5)           ; => 50
(math/lerp 10 20 0.5)           ; => 15
(math/lerp 100 0 0.9)           ; => 10
```

You can extrapolate too ‚Äî pass `t` outside `[0, 1]` and the verb happily returns values past the endpoints. That is a feature, not a bug; it lets a spring-easing overshoot the target and settle back.

---

## Aggregates: `math/sum`, `math/avg`

Both take a list. `math/sum` returns the sum. `math/avg` returns the arithmetic mean.

```scheme
(math/sum '(1 2 3 4 5))         ; => 15
(math/sum '(10))                ; => 10
(math/avg '(4 6 8))             ; => 6
(math/avg '(2 2 2 2))           ; => 2
```

Both verbs are defensive about the empty list ‚Äî pass `'()` and you get zero for `sum` and nothing meaningful for `avg` (division by zero). Prefer `(if (null? xs) 0 (math/avg xs))` when the list might be empty.

---

## Comparison: `math/compare`

The three-way comparator most sort routines want. Returns `-1` if `a < b`, `0` if `a = b`, and `1` if `a > b`.

```scheme
(math/compare 5 3)              ; => 1
(math/compare 3 3)              ; => 0
(math/compare 1 5)              ; => -1
```

Use it as the ordering function when writing your own sort: `(sort xs math/compare)`.

---

## Number theory: `math/lcm`

Least common multiple. Given two integers, `math/lcm` returns the smallest positive integer that both divide evenly.

```scheme
(math/lcm 4 6)                  ; => 12
(math/lcm 3 5)                  ; => 15
(math/lcm 12 18)                ; => 36
(math/lcm 7 1)                  ; => 7
```

The classic use is adding fractions with unlike denominators: `(math/lcm 4 6)` tells you that `1/4 + 1/6` should be re-expressed over a denominator of 12.

---

## Logarithms: `math/log2`, `math/log10`

The two most common non-natural logarithms. `math/log2` counts binary halvings; `math/log10` counts decimal digits.

```scheme
(math/log2 8)                   ; => 3
(math/log2 1024)                ; => 10
(math/log10 100)                ; => 2
(math/log10 1)                  ; => 0
(math/log10 1000000)            ; => 6
```

`math/log2` of a positive integer that is not a power of two returns a non-integer ‚Äî for instance `(math/log2 10)` is about `3.32`. That is the number of bits you need to represent ten distinct values.

---

## Number-line rendering: `math/integer-line`, `math/number-line`

Both return a list of numbers you can render as ticks on a line. `math/integer-line` steps by one over an integer range; `math/number-line` accepts an arbitrary step.

```scheme
(math/integer-line -3 3)        ; => (-3 -2 -1 0 1 2 3)
(math/integer-line 0 5)         ; => (0 1 2 3 4 5)
(math/number-line 0 10 2)       ; => (0 2 4 6 8 10)
(math/number-line 0 1 0.25)     ; => (0 0.25 0.5 0.75 1)
```

These lists are inspectable data ‚Äî you can `(map ...)` over them, `(length ...)` them, or hand them to a drawing routine that paints ticks at each position.

---

## Counting on and skip-counting: `math/count-on`, `math/skip-count`

`math/count-on` is what a first-grader does when asked \"start at five and count on three more.\" It returns the list of numbers reached. `math/skip-count` is what a second-grader does when learning multiplication tables: count in twos, or fives, or tens.

```scheme
(math/count-on 5 3)             ; => (5 6 7)
(math/count-on 20 5)            ; => (20 21 22 23 24)
(math/skip-count 0 5 4)         ; => (0 5 10 15)
(math/skip-count 10 3 5)        ; => (10 13 16 19 22)
(math/skip-count 100 -10 5)     ; => (100 90 80 70 60)
```

Note the argument order for `skip-count`: `(math/skip-count start step count)`. A negative step counts *down*, which is how you introduce subtraction as \"skipping backward.\"

---

## Place-value pedagogy: `math/digit-at`, `math/expanded-form`

`math/digit-at` extracts the digit at a given power of ten. Place 0 is the ones place, place 1 is the tens place, and so on. `math/expanded-form` returns the list of non-zero place-value components.

```scheme
(math/digit-at 12345 0)         ; => 5
(math/digit-at 12345 1)         ; => 4
(math/digit-at 12345 3)         ; => 2
(math/expanded-form 342)        ; => (300 40 2)
(math/expanded-form 1007)       ; => (1000 7)
```

Zeros drop out of expanded form because there is nothing to say about them. `342 = 300 + 40 + 2`; the tens digit of `1007` is zero, so it contributes nothing.

---

## Fraction pedagogy: `math/fraction-bar`, `math/mixed-number`, `math/ratio-bar`

These three verbs return *tagged data*. The first element of each returned list is a symbol identifying the shape; the remaining elements are the parts. A UI adapter can render them; at the REPL you inspect them as data.

```scheme
(math/fraction-bar 3 4)         ; => (fraction-bar 3 4 0.75)
(math/fraction-bar 5 8)         ; => (fraction-bar 5 8 0.625)
(math/mixed-number 1 1 2)       ; => (mixed-number 1 1 2 1.5)
(math/mixed-number 2 3 4)       ; => (mixed-number 2 3 4 2.75)
(math/ratio-bar 2 3)            ; => (ratio-bar 2 3 0.6666666666666666)
```

The last element of each tuple is the decimal value ‚Äî useful when you want to `>` two fractions without doing the cross-multiply by hand. `(math/mixed-number whole num den)` reads as *whole and num-over-den*, e.g. `(math/mixed-number 1 1 2)` is one-and-a-half.

---

## Area and multiplication models: `math/area-model`

Returns `(area-model a b product)` ‚Äî the ingredients a UI needs to draw an `a`-by-`b` grid of unit squares, with `a*b` marked as the product.

```scheme
(math/area-model 4 6)           ; => (area-model 4 6 24)
(math/area-model 12 8)          ; => (area-model 12 8 96)
(math/area-model 3 3)           ; => (area-model 3 3 9)
```

Use it when you want to *show* multiplication rather than just compute it. The tagged shape is the answer plus its visual recipe.

---

## Arbitrary bases: `math/log-base`

`math/log-base` computes the logarithm of a number in an arbitrary base. `(math/log-base n b)` ‚Äî note the argument order: the number *first*, the base *second*.

```scheme
(math/log-base 100 10)          ; => 2
(math/log-base 8 2)             ; => 3
(math/log-base 27 3)            ; => 3.0000000000000004
(math/log-base 1 5)             ; => 0
```

Watch the third example: `27` is exactly `3^3`, but floating-point long division gives an answer that is one ulp above three. Any comparison to a whole number should use a tolerance, not `=`.

---

## Vectors: `vec/make`, `vec/add`, `vec/sub`, `vec/scale`

A vector in Motoi is a plain list of numbers. `vec/make` accepts any number of components ‚Äî two for planar work, three for space, more if you have a reason. Every other vec verb dispatches on the length.

```scheme
(vec/make 3 4)                  ; => (3 4)
(vec/make 1 2 3)                ; => (1 2 3)
(vec/add (vec/make 1 2) (vec/make 3 4))    ; => (4 6)
(vec/sub (vec/make 5 5) (vec/make 1 2))    ; => (4 3)
(vec/scale (vec/make 3 4) 2)               ; => (6 8)
```

Addition and subtraction are element-wise. Scaling multiplies every component by the same scalar. There are aliases `vec/+` and `vec/-` for people who prefer symbolic names.

---

## Vector distance and interpolation: `vec/distance`, `vec/lerp`

`vec/distance` is Euclidean distance between two vectors of the same length. `vec/lerp` linearly interpolates between two vectors component-by-component.

```scheme
(vec/distance (vec/make 0 0) (vec/make 3 4))       ; => 5
(vec/distance (vec/make 1 1) (vec/make 4 5))       ; => 5
(vec/lerp (vec/make 0 0) (vec/make 10 10) 0.5)     ; => (5 5)
(vec/lerp (vec/make 0 0) (vec/make 100 0) 0.25)    ; => (25 0)
```

`vec/lerp` is the vector version of `math/lerp` ‚Äî same rules, more dimensions. Pass `t = 0` and you get the first vector; pass `t = 1` and you get the second; pass something in between and you glide.

---

## Zero vectors and dimension queries: `vec/zero`, `vec/dim`

`vec/zero` returns the zero vector. Called with no argument it defaults to a 2-vector; pass an integer to get a longer one. `vec/dim` reports how many components a vector has.

```scheme
(vec/zero)                      ; => ()
(vec/zero 3)                    ; => (0 0 0)
(vec/dim (vec/make 3 4))        ; => 2
(vec/dim (vec/make 1 2 3))      ; => 3
(vec/dim (vec/zero 5))          ; => 5
```

Careful with `(vec/zero)` ‚Äî with no arguments it returns the empty list, which is *not* the 2-vector `(0 0)`. Pass an explicit dimension whenever the code around it assumes a specific shape.

---

## Point translation: `geom/translate`

`geom/translate` moves a point by an offset. The point is a two-element list ‚Äî `(x y)` ‚Äî and the offsets are scalars.

```scheme
(geom/translate (geom/point 5 5) 3 2)          ; => (8 7)
(geom/translate (geom/point 0 0) 10 20)        ; => (10 20)
(geom/translate (geom/point 100 100) -50 -50)  ; => (50 50)
```

Same idea as `vec/add` but the argument shape is different: two scalars instead of a vector. Use whichever verb reads more naturally at the call site ‚Äî a translation *feels* like moving a point, an addition *feels* like combining two vectors.

---

## Polygon area: `geom/polygon-area`

Given a list of `(x y)` vertices ‚Äî in order, forming a closed polygon ‚Äî returns the enclosed area. Uses the shoelace formula, so it works for any simple polygon: triangles, quadrilaterals, stars.

```scheme
(geom/polygon-area '((0 0) (4 0) (4 3) (0 3)))    ; => 12
(geom/polygon-area '((0 0) (10 0) (5 10)))        ; => 50
(geom/polygon-area '((0 0) (2 0) (2 2) (0 2)))    ; => 4
```

The first example is a 4x3 rectangle (area 12), the second a triangle with base 10 and height 10 (area 50), the third a 2x2 square. The vertices should trace the perimeter without crossing themselves ‚Äî a self-intersecting polygon confuses the shoelace formula.

---

## Randomness: `randint`, `random-range`, `random-pick`

`randint` returns an integer in the half-open range `[a, b)`. `random-range` returns a float in `[a, b)` ‚Äî always a float, even when both bounds are integers. `random-pick` returns one uniformly chosen element from a list.

```scheme
(randint 0 100)                                          ; => 42   (varies)
(random-range 10 20)                                     ; => 14.7 (varies)
(random-pick '(apple pear plum))                         ; => pear (varies)
(list (randint 0 10) (randint 0 10))                     ; => (7 4)  (varies)
```

Without a seed, `randint`, `random-range`, and `random-pick` all draw from the process's shared random stream ‚Äî fresh values each call.

`with-seed` binds a fresh pseudorandom stream for the enclosed thunk. Within a single session it reproduces the same sequence for the same seed; across separate `bin/motoi eval` invocations the underlying stream may start in a different place, so pin values with tests rather than trusting a specific literal from the docs.

```scheme
(with-seed 1 (lambda () (randint 0 100)))                ; => varies per session
(with-seed 42 (lambda () (list (randint 0 10) (randint 0 10))))  ; => varies per session
```

Prefer `with-seed` when the shape of the value matters (\"give me a list of three ints in `[0, 100)`\") more than the exact values. For screenshot-grade determinism, run the whole cart under `with-seed` and compare shapes, not literals.

---

## Closing note

Every example in this appendix was checked against `bin/motoi eval` on 2026-07-17. If a future refactor moves a verb or changes its return shape, this appendix is where you would see the drift first ‚Äî and where you should fix it.
")
